<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Signet Bank Student Loans Dictionary</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY

BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#008040" VLINK="#800040" ALINK="#804040"><P

><A HREF="toc1.html"><IMG

SRC="images/artb_bk.jpg" ALT="Book Icon" BORDER="0" HEIGHT='100"' WIDTH="89" ALIGN="left"></A>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG

SRC="images/xbtn_edu.jpg" ALT="Educational Funding Button" BORDER="0" HEIGHT="89" WIDTH="100" ALIGN="right"></A></P>

<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Signet Bank's </FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+2">Dictionary

of College Financing Words &amp; Phrases</FONT></B></CENTER>

<UL>

<LI>FREE Student and Parent Loan <A HREF="psorder.html"> Applications</A>.

</LI>

<LI>Take a Look at the <A HREF="bkorder.html"><B>Book Store</B></A>.

</LI>

<LI>Financial Aid Officer and High School Guidance Counselor

<A HREF="faoform.html"> Supply Room</A>.

</LI>

<LI>Or You Can Call Signet for More Information: <B>1-800-434-1988</B>

</LI></UL>

<P>

 </P>

<PRE></PRE>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/banr_bar.jpg"></CENTER>

<P>



<B>ACCRUED INTEREST.</B><BR> Interest which accrues on a loan(s) and is

payable by the borrower or federal government.  Each day interest is calculated

on the unpaid principal balance and becomes &quot;accrued interest.&quot;

</P>

<P>

<B>AMORTIZATION.</B><BR> The gradual reduction of a loan debt by periodic

installment (usually monthly) payments of principal and interest.

</P>

<P>

<B>CANCELLATION</B>.<BR> Some student loan programs allow for either a portion

or the total loan to be canceled due to certain provisions.

</P>

<P>

<B>CAPITALIZATION.</B><BR> Accrued interest is added to the principal balance

of the loan.

</P>

<P>



<B>CONSOLIDATION LOAN.</B><BR> A way to refinance all of your exiting loans by

combining them into one new loan.  Usually a consolidation loan has a lower

monthly payment and a longer term than your combined original loans.

</P>

<P>

<B>CONSUMER CREDIT COUNSELING SERVICE.</B><BR> A free public service agency

that will help you learn how to stay on a budget and make your loan payments on

time.  Most areas have Consumer Credit Counseling Services; look in the yellow

pages of your local telephone book for the number.

</P>

<P>

<B>CREDIT BUREAU.</B><BR> A company that maintains records on individuals'

financial transactions. Lenders check with credit bureaus to learn whether a

customer who wants a loan is likely to repay based on the way the customer has

handled other financial obligations in the past.

</P>

<P>

<B>DEFAULT.</B><BR> The failure of the borrower to make an installment payment

when due or to meet other terms of the promissory note; and it is reasonable to

conclude that the borrower no longer intends to honor the obligation to repay. 

Once a loan goes into default, the lender can take legal action against the

borrower subject to the terms of the loan agreement.  In the case of the student

loans, the government may also take action.

</P>

<P>

<B>DEFERMENT.</B><BR> An approved postponement of payment for a specified

period which may be granted if the borrower falls into certain

government-established categories.

</P>

<P>

<B>DELINQUENCY.</B><BR> The status of a loan when at least one payment has

been missed.

</P>

<P>

<B>DELINQUENT.</B><BR> The borrower fails to make an installment payment when

due or to meet other terms of the promissory note.

</P>

<P>

<B>DISBURSEMENT.</B><BR> The date the loan check is issued by the lender.

</P>

<P>

<B>EXIT INTERVIEW.</B><BR> A discussion you will have with your school's

financial aid representative held shortly before you leave school.  One purpose

of the interview is to give you information about repaying your student loans.

</P>

<P>

<B>FEDERAL PLUS.</B><BR> (Parent Loans for Undergraduate Students)  A

government-backed loan designed for parents of financially dependent students.

</P>

<P>

<B>FEDERAL SLS.</B><BR> (Supplemental Loan for Students)  A government-backed

loan designed for students who are financially independent.  This program was

eliminated effective 7/1/94, and the loan limits for Unsubsidized Federal

Stafford Loans were increased for independent students.

</P>

<P>

<B>FEDERAL STAFFORD SUBSIDIZED STUDENT LOAN.</B><BR> (formerly Guaranteed

Student Loan, GSL)  A need based government-backed student loan designed for

students attending school at least half-time.

</P>

<P>

<B>FEDERAL STAFFORD UNSUBSIDIZED STUDENT LOAN.</B><BR> This loan is not based

on need, allowing students all income and asset levels the eligibility for a

lower cost student loan.

</P>

<P>

<B>FORBEARANCE.</B><BR> A temporary postponement or reduction of student loan

payments which may be granted if the lender decides that the borrower has a

financial hardship.

</P>

<P>

<B>GARNISHING.</B><BR> The deduction from the borrower's funds a portion of a

borrower's payment--with or without the borrower's consent.  A lender may take

this action in order to force repayment of a loan that is in default.

</P>

<P>

<B>GRACE PERIOD.</B><BR> A six or nine-month period before the borrower enters

repayment.

</P>

<P>

<B>GUARANTEE AGENCY</B>.<BR> A state or private non-profit agency that

administers a student loan insurance program, e.g., United Student Aid Funds

(USAF).

</P>

<P>

<B>HOLDER.</B><BR> The entity which holds a legally effective promissory note

and which has the right to collect from the borrower.

</P>

<P>

<B>INTEREST.  </B>  <BR> The amount that a lender charges a borrower for the

use of money that has been loaned.

</P>

<P>

<B>MAKER.</B><BR> The borrower.

</P>

<P>

<B>PRINCIPAL.  </B><BR> When you take out a loan, the principal is the full

amount you have borrowed. When you are repaying the loan, the principal is the

portion of the original amount you still owe.

</P>

<P>

<B>PROMISSORY NOTE.</B><BR> A written promise to pay, at a specified time, a

sum of money to a specified person or holder.

</P>

<P>

<B>REPAYMENT SCHEDULE.  </B><BR> A document your lender(s) will send to you

after you leave school, listing the total amount you owe, the amount of your

monthly payment and the date your first payment is due.

</P>

<P>

<B>SECONDARY MARKET</B>.<BR> A state or private agency that purchases loans

from lenders.

</P>

<P>

<B>SERIALIZATION.</B>  <BR> The combining of several loans, all of the same

type, held by various lenders. Students must find a lender willing to purchase

loans from other lenders.

</P>

<P>

<B>SERVICER.</B><BR> The entity designated to track and collect a loan on

behalf of the holder.

</P>

<P>

<B>TERM.</B>   <BR> The amount of time you have to repay your loan.

</P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/banr_bar.jpg"></CENTER>  

