</strong>
 | <strong>
<a href="cis1296.htm">4th Quarter Income Statement</a>
</strong> | <strong>
<a href="finhi1296.htm">4th Quarter Financial Highlights</a>
</strong> | <strong>
<a href="finrpts.htm">Financial Reports</a>
</strong>
</center>
<p>  
<h1>Signet Banking Corporation Reports Earnings</h1>
<p>
<font size=+1>
RICHMOND, Va. - (Jan 22, 1997) - Signet Banking Corporation today reported earnings of $33.6 million, or $.55 per share, for the fourth quarter of 1996 and $124.9 million, or $2.06 per share, for the year.  In 1995, Signet reported earnings of $9.0 million, or $.15 per share, for the fourth quarter and $111.1 million, or $1.86 per share, for the full year.  
<P>
<P>Reported results for 1995 included charges for a commercial fraud loss and earnings of Capital One Financial Corporation prior to its spin-off to shareholders on February 28, 1995.  Adjusting for these items, net income for the 1996 fourth quarter and the full year rose 6 percent over the comparable periods in 1995.  On the same basis, earnings per share increased 4 percent in 1996 above 1995 fourth quarter and full-year levels.
<P>
<P>Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Malcolm S. McDonald said that the company was pleased with the vibrant revenue and asset growth and credit quality.  "We accomplished a great deal during the year through innovative marketing and risk management techniques. Targeted commercial and consumer businesses were very well-received in the marketplace.  Loan-by-check outstandings, despite a six-month hiatus in marketing, grew 80 percent.  We are encouraged by promising early results for gathering deposits by mail, and are experiencing good response to several other commercial and consumer products and services.  We capped the year by completing our first student loan securitization in December." 
<P>
<P>The managed loan portfolio (loans and securitized assets) grew $949 million to $7.4 billion at December 31, 1996.  Robust loan growth in both the commercial and consumer sectors spurred 15 percent annual growth in the portfolio, even as Signet continued to reduce its commercial real estate lending exposure.  Focused regional and national middle market specialties and lease financing accounted for most of the growth in commercial loans which rose $360 million, or 12 percent, in 1996.  Direct-response installment lending fueled the 20 percent increase in managed consumer loans, which reached $3.4 billion at year-end.
<P>
<P>Non-performing assets decreased 29 percent during the year to $38.8 million, or .61 percent of balance sheet loans and foreclosed properties, compared with $54.3 million, or 1 percent, at the end of 1995.  Net charge-offs in 1996 were $66.8 million, or 1.13 percent of average loans, and $53.1 million, or .87 percent, in 1995.  Excluding the loan-by-check risk tests, the net charge-off ratio was .74 percent in 1996.
<P>
<P>Signet provided $29.8 million in the fourth quarter, and $73.9 million for the full year of 1996, to the allowance for loan losses.  At December 31, 1996, the loan loss allowance of $136.7 million equaled 352 percent of non-performing assets and 2.15 percent of loans outstanding.
<P>
<P>Total revenues (net interest income and non-interest income) for the quarter were $206.3 million and $748.3 million for the year.  Total revenues were 12 percent higher than the 1995 fourth quarter, and up 13 percent year-over-year, excluding Capital One.  Non-interest income benefited from strong trading gains and securitizations.  Signets net interest margin was 4.56 percent, down from 4.70 percent in the previous quarter.  Funding costs remained fairly stable in 1996 while asset yields adjusted to lower base rates, accounting for most of the decrease in the net interest margin.
<P>
<P>Non-interest expense for the fourth quarter and the full year was $125.3 million and $485.3 million, respectively.  Adjusting for Capital One and the fraud loss in 1995, non-interest expense grew 8 percent as a result of higher staff and marketing expenses in 1996.  In October, Signet initiated a company-wide redesign program to realign its infrastructure and improve efficiency.  Implementation of the redesign will begin in mid 1997.  The efficiency ratio was 65 percent for 1996. 
<P>
<P>The 1996 return on equity was 14.4 percent and the return on average assets was 1.1 percent. The equity-to-asset ratio was 7.9 percent.
<P>
<P>Signet is a $12 billion financial institution with headquarters in Richmond, Virginia. The company offers a wide array of financial services through its Capital Markets, Commercial and Consumer Banking businesses. Signet has offices in Virginia, Maryland and the District of Columbia, and markets several of its products nationally.
<P>

<p>
<br>
