<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
<TITLE>Commitment to Communities</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#008040" VLINK="#800040" ALINK="#804040">
</HEAD>
<h2 align=center>Commitment to Our Communities</h2>
<a href="/signet/cinfo.htm">
<img src="images/xbtn_inf.jpg" 
alt="Corporate Information Button" 
hspace=5 vspace=5 border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=LEFT >
</a> 
<a href="http://www.signet.com/">
<img src="images/xbtn_hom.jpg" 
alt="Signet Homepage Button" 
border=0  height=89 width =100  ALIGN=RIGHT>
</a>
<BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="images/banr_bar.jpg"></center>
<BR><BR><BR>
<p>
<font size=+1>Since opening our doors in 1922 as the Morris Plan Bank 
of Richmond, Signet has been focused on meeting consumers' needs. 
Our goals have been accomplished in many ways:  by developing new 
products, by expanding the ways we deliver services, by identifying 
new community partners, and by improving communication with both 
individuals and community groups in our market areas.  As 
Signet moves toward becoming a financial services company for the 
next century, our commitment remains unchanged.
<p>
Signet's community reinvestment program strives to understand the 
diverse needs of our communities and to respond in a timely, 
effective manner.  We accomplish this mission 
through one-on-one discussions with community leaders and 
neighborhood groups; ongoing and consistent outreach; continual analysis 
of lending and service efforts; market surveys; active 
participation in community planning; and feedback from customers, 
employees and our <a href="bod.htm">Board of Directors.</a>
<p>
Another important element of community reinvestment is the active 
involvement of our senior management, Board, and specialized 
staff.  Viable and responsive community reinvestment activity demands 
access and participation at all levels of our company.  
The Board determines the community reinvestment policies that govern 
Signet's community initiatives.  Senior managers and business-unit 
leaders manages these policies, and community reinvestment 
professionals coordinate our corporate and regional programs.
<p>
Finally, we believe our community reinvestment efforts should link 
strong and viable community groups, government agencies, and 
for-profit entities into driving forces that will promote 
progress and revitalization.  We are committed to using all 
our resources -- lending, investments, contributions, and 
people -- in the redevelopment of Signet communities.
<p>
Whether providing lending expertise to a developer, uniting community 
groups toward a common goal, linking fellow banks in a joint 
project, sponsoring a forum to educate the public about 
housing or small business issues, supporting the operation of 
a nonprofit organization, or counseling individuals so they can 
earn a better credit rating, Signet extends its best resources 
to create the right answers for the challenges facing our 
communities.
<p>
The following pages provide an overview of our community reinvestment 
efforts and a snapshot of several 1995 activities involving Signet 
and our community partners.  We welcome your comments about 
these or other Signet community reinvestment initiatives.
<p>
</font>

<center><a href="crastmt.htm">Community Programs</a>
 | <a href="neamiah.htm"><strong>The Nehemiah Project</a>
 | <a href="rnhs.htm">Richmond Neighborhood Housing Services</a>
 | <a href="nornck.htm">Northern Neck Housing</a>
 | <a href="btbcra.htm">Back to Basics</a>
 | <a href="markting.htm"> Reaching Communities </a>
<p><BR><CENTER><IMG SRC="images/banr_bar.jpg"></center>
<P>

