<DOCNO>WT25-B11-107</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA076-000505-B012-266</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://jerome.signet.com:80/perfinance/glossary.htm 206.151.85.34 19970124031932 text/html 10723
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Friday, 24-Jan-97 03:18:39 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 31-May-96 19:54:34 GMT
Content-length: 10534
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Signet Definition Glossary</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#008040" VLINK="#800040" ALINK="#804040">
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><IMG SRC="images/logobchr.jpg" ALT="Signet Logo" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=38 BORDER=0></a>
<CENTER><a href="conindex.htm"><img src="images/xbtn_per.jpg" alt="Personal Finance Button"  border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ></a>
<FONT SIZE=+4><EM>  Glossary</EM></FONT>
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><img src="images/xbtn_hom.jpg" alt="Signet Homepage Button" border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE ></a><BR>
<a href="checkinf.htm"><img src="images/artc_cbk.jpg" alt="Checking Image" border=0  height=44 width =50 ></a>
<a href="saveinfo.htm"><img src="images/artc_coi.jpg" alt="Savings Image" border=0  height=44 width =50></A>
<a href="lendinfo.htm"><img src="images/artc_car.jpg" alt="Lending Image" border=0  height=44 width =50></A>
<BR>
<A HREF ="checkinf.htm">Checking</A> | <A HREF ="saveinfo.htm">Savings</A> | <A HREF ="lendinfo.htm">Lending</A>
</CENTER>
<p><CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER>
<P>
<p><b>Adjustable Rate Mortgage (ARM, also called Variable Rate Mortgage):</b>
A mortgage with an interest rate that adjusts periodically to reflect changes
in market conditions. Your mortgage payments are adjusted up or down (usually
on an annual basis) as the interest rate changes. To protect you in a rising
interest market, rate increases are limited (usually 2 percentage points
annually; 6 percentage points over the life of the loan).<P>

<p> <b>Annual Membership/Participation Fee:</b> An amount that is charged
annually for having a line of credit available. It is charged regardless
of whether or not you use the line.<P>

<p> <b>Annual Percentage Rate (APR):</b> The cost of credit on a yearly
basis expressed as a percentage. (In the case of a mortgage, this rate also
includes points and other associated costs, therefore it is usually higher
than the advertised simple interest rate. The APR more accurately reflects
what you'll be paying and allows you to compare different mortgages based
on actual costs.)<P>

<p> <b>Application Fee:</b> Fees that are paid upon application for your
loan or credit line. It may include charges for property appraisal and
a credit report.<P>

<p> <b>Appraisal:</b> An estimate of the value of a home, made by a professional
appraiser. The maximum amount of the mortgage is usually based on the appraisal.<P>

<p> <b>Balloon Payment:</b> A lump-sum payment that you may be required
to make under a plan when the plan ends.
<P>

<STRONG>Blended Interest:</STRONG>  Using this method of calculating account interest, you earn a base rate on balances up to a fixed amount, a higher rate on balances above the first level ceiling up to a second fixed amount, and the highest rate on the remaining balance.<P>

<p> <b>Cap:</b> A limit on how much the variable-interest rate can increase
during the life of the plan.<P>

<p> <b>Closing Costs:</b> Fees paid at closing, such as attorney's fees,
fees for preparing and filing a mortage, for taxes, title search, and insurance.
While closing costs depend on your state and county, as a rule of thumb,
closing costs usually add up to 3 to 6 percent of the mortgage principal amount.<P>

<STRONG>Compound Interest: </STRONG> Occurs when interest earned on a balance is added to the balance, and interest is calculated on the accumulated balance.
<P>

<p> <b>Credit Limit:</b> The maximum amount that you can borrow under a home equity plan, a line of credit or a credit card.<P>

<STRONG>EFT:</STRONG>  EFT or electronic funds transfer is a technology that enables account holders to move money quickly and safely from one account to another.  Linked by an international network, electronically transferred funds can be sent throughout the world and be available in the specified account the next business day.
<P>
<p> <b>Equity:</b> The difference between the fair market value (appraised
value) of your home and your outstanding mortgage balance(s). If you make
a 5 percent down payment, you have 5 percent of the price of your home
in equity. Provided the value of your home remains stable, then as you make payments toward the principal over time, the equity
in your home grows.  Any increase in the value of your home also adds to your equity<P>

<p> <b>Escrow:</b> A special third-party account set up by the lender in
which a portion of your monthly payment funds are held to pay for taxes,
insurance and other items. &quot;Escrow&quot; can also refer to a third
party who carries out the instructions of both the buyer and seller to
handle the paperwork at the settlement.<P>

<STRONG>FDIC:</STRONG>  The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation is the regulatory agency that provides deposit insurance. For more information on deposit insurance, please refer to http://www.fdic.gov/fdicyid.html.
<P>

<STRONG>Fixed Interest Rate:</STRONG>  An interest rate on an account that does not change.  
<P>

<p> <b>Fixed Rate Mortgage:</b> A mortgage with an interest rate that stays
the same (fixed) over the life of the mortgage. Monthly payments for a
fixed rate mortgage are very stable.<P>

<STRONG>Floating Interest:</STRONG>  Floating or variable interest occurs when the interest rate on an account is tied to an  index, for example a bank's prime rate.  When the index changes, prime in this case, the account rate adjusts accordingly.
<P>
<p> <b>Good Faith Estimate:</b> A document provided at application that
provides estimates of all costs associated with obtaining and closing a
mortgage loan.<P>

<p> <b>Index:</b> The base for rate changes that the financial institution uses to determine
how much the annual percentage rate or yield will change over time, for example, the prime rate.<P>

<p> <b>Interest Rate:</b> For loans, the periodic charge, expressed as a percentage rate to be charged. For deposits, the periodic rate paid on the deposit balance.
<P>
<p> <b>Loan-to-Value Ratio:</b> The relationship between the appraised
value of property at closing and the loan amount.<P>

<p> <b>Margin:</b> The number of percentage points the lender adds to the
index to determine the annual percentage rate to be charged, for example, prime plus one.<P>

<STRONG>Maturity:</STRONG>  The end of an investment or savings product term.  At this time the account owner receives the initial investment plus accumulated interest.
<P>

<p> <b>Minimum Payment:</b> The minimum amount that you must pay (usually
monthly) on your account. In some plans, the minimum payment may be &quot;interest
only.&quot; In other plans, the minimum payment may include principal and
interest.<P>

<p> <b>Origination Fee:</b> The fee charged by a lender to take a mortgage application and underwrite a mortgage, sometimes combined with discount points, and may be combined with document preparation fee.<P>

<p> <b>Payment Frequency:</b> How often you make a payment on your loan,
thus decreasing your principal and interest due. Typically either bi-weekly,
monthly, quarterly, or annually.<P>

<p> <b>PITI (Principal-Interest-Taxes-Insurances):</b> Abbreviation for
the parts of a typical monthly mortgage payment.<P>

<p> <b>Points:</b> A point is equal to one percent of the amount of your loan. Points usually are collected at closing, and are in addition to monthly interest.  Payment of discount points usually results in a lower interest rate on the loan.<P>

<p> <b>Prepaids:</b> The amounts that are put into escrow at closing,
usually including real estate taxes, insurance, and interest from the settlement date to the end of the month.<P>

<p> <b>Principal:</b> The amount of money that you owe. This will
decrease with every payment, unless payments are "interest only". This is also the amount of money on which your
interest is calculated.<P>

<p> <b>Private Mortgage Insurance (PMI):</b> An insurance policy the borrower
buys to protect the lender from non-payment of the loan. PMI policies are
usually required if you make a down payment that is below 20% of the value of the home.<P>

<p> <b>Security Interest:</b> An interest, such as a lien, that a lender takes in the borrower's
property to assure repayment of a debt.<P>

<STRONG>Tiered Interest:</STRONG>  Calculating interest this way, a single rate is applied to the entire account balance.
<P>
<p> <b>Title Insurance:</b> An insurance policy which insures you and/or the lender against errors in the title search of the property.<P>

<p> <b>Transaction Fee:</b> A fee imposed by the financial institution as a result of the customer conducting certain transactions, such as each time you draw on your credit line or withdraw funds from your account using another institution's ATM.<P>

<p> <b>Variable Rate:</b> An interest rate that changes periodically in
relation to an index. Payments may increase or decrease accordingly.<P>

<STRONG>Yield:</STRONG>  Represents the amount earned as a percentage of the amount contributed.
<P>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1><I>Signet Bank, Member FDIC<BR>
Equal Housing Lender</I></FONT></CENTER>

<CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER>

