<html>
<head>
   <title>Signet Credit Cards and Lines of Credit</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#008040" VLINK="#800040" ALINK="#804040">
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><IMG SRC="images/logobchr.jpg" ALT="Signet Logo" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=38 BORDER=0></a>
<CENTER><a href="conindex.htm"><img src="images/xbtn_per.jpg" alt="Personal Finance Button"  border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ></a><FONT SIZE=+3><EM>Credit Cards</EM></FONT>
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><img src="images/xbtn_hom.jpg" alt="Signet Homepage Button" border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE ></a><BR> <FONT SIZE=+2><I>and</I></FONT><BR> <FONT SIZE=+3><I>Lines of Credit</I></FONT></CENTER>

<CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>Credit cards are becoming more and more important in today's society.
You can use your credit card at almost any merchant to purchase just about anything
imaginable. The best thing about a credit card is convenience. You don't
need to carry cash with you, and when you're in a jam it can come to the
rescue. For the added convenience and overwhelming acceptance of credit
cards, an annual fee is generally charged for credit cards.  Where extended credit is granted (that is, for purchases not paid off each month), an annual percentage rate (APR) is charged.

<p> Most credit cards allow a grace period on purchases until the billing
date. This means that interest will not be charged on those purchases that
were made during the statement period. If you choose not to pay off your
balance, interest will accrue, typically beginning on the payment due date, although this may vary. This is
typically different for cash advances, however. Cash advances can be made
at any bank or financial institution (including ATMs) that accept credit
cards (e.g. Master Card&reg; or Visa&reg;). You may receive any amount of cash up
to your cash advance limit and interest begins to accrue on the date the
cash is received. Often times credit card companies will offer special
low APRs on cash advances and balance transfers for a limited time. Many
times your credit limit and APR will be different for purchases and cash
advances. 

<p> A credit card is a very convenient tool and can be used for just about
anything, but a word of caution: keep track of your credit card spending to ensure
that your credit card bill doesn't exceed your ability to make timely repayments. </p>

<p>Another form of credit that is similar to an installment loan is a line
of credit. A line of credit is similar to an installment loan in that you
borrow a set amount of money (e.g. $5000), however the difference is, if
you pay off a portion of that money (e.g. $1000) you can borrow again up
to your original limit (i.e. you can borrow that $1000 again), as long as you are complying with the terms of the loan. A line of credit is typically extended for a set period of time and during that time you can have as much outstanding as
your limit will allow, and in this respect it is much like a credit card.</FONT> </p>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1><EM>Equal Opportunity Lender</EM></FONT></CENTER>
<P><CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER><P>
