<html>
<head>
   <title>Signet Mortgages </title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.0GoldB1 (Win32)">
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#008040" VLINK="#800040" ALINK="#804040">
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><IMG SRC="images/logobchr.jpg" ALT="Signet Logo" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=38 BORDER=0></a>
<CENTER><a href="conindex.htm"><img src="images/xbtn_per.jpg" alt="Personal Finance Button"  border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE  ></a><FONT SIZE=+4><EM> Mortgages </EM></FONT>
<a href="http://www.signet.com/"><img src="images/xbtn_hom.jpg" alt="Signet Homepage Button" border=0  height=89 width =100 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE ></a><BR></CENTER>

<CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER><P>

<FONT SIZE=+1>Many long-time renters and first-time home buyers don't think they
can afford a home, believing that a monthly mortgage payment is always
larger than a rent payment. Others think that you have to have a lot of
money in savings for a down payment and closing costs. And some presume
that anything negative in their credit history will disqualify them from
obtaining a mortgage. Low to moderate income families also may believe
that they cannot afford a mortgage. However, there are many opportunities
that exist through government subsidized programs. Contact your loan officer
for more details. These misconceptions keep many eligible buyers on the sideline.

<p> Read the information below for basic explanations of the different
types of mortgages available. If you would like an explanation of
any of the terms being used click on the <a HREF="glossary.htm">glossary</a> link at any time to view the definitions of commonly used jargon.</p>

<CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER><P>

<h3>Three Mortgages-Many Options</h3>

<br>Although there are many options for a first mortgage loan, they
all fall into one of these three general categories: 
<ol>
<li><b>Fixed Rate Mortgages:</b> Monthly payments for interest and
principal stay the same for the life of the loan. Property taxes and
homeowners insurance may increase and cause an increase in the monthly loan payment, but generally the monthly payments
will be very stable.</li>

<p> Fixed rate mortgages are available for a variety of term lengths. The
shorter the term, the higher the payment. There are also &quot;bi-weekly&quot;
mortgages, which shorten the term of the loan - saving you literally tens
of thousands of dollars in interest - by calling for payment of half the
monthly payment every two weeks. (Since there are 52 weeks in a year, you
make 26 payments, which is the equivalent of making 13 monthly payments
every year.)
<p><a HREF="glossary.htm">glossary</a>
<br></p>

<li><b>Adjustable Rate Mortgages (ARMs):</b> These loans generally begin
with an interest rate that is 2-3 percent below a comparable fixed rate
mortage, and could allow you to buy a more expensive home. For some, the
lower starting interest rate - and resulting lower monthly payments -
make home ownership possible.</li>

<p> With an ARM, the interest rate is subject to change at specified intervals
(for example, every year) depending on changing market conditions; if interest
rates go up, your monthly payment will go up, too. However, if rates go
down, your mortgage payment will drop also.</p>

<p> To protect you over a long period, ARMs have an interest rate maximum or "cap".
You'll know, upfront, the highest interest rate you would ever have to
pay on your ARM.</p>

<p> There are also mortgages that combine aspects of fixed and adjustable rate
mortgages - starting at a low fixed rate for 3, 5, 7, or 10 years, for
example, then adjusting to market conditions on an annual basis for the remaining
term.
<p><a HREF="glossary.htm">glossary</a></p>

<li><b>Balloon Mortgages:</b> These mortgages offer low, fixed-rate payments
as though the mortgage were a 30-year term. But instead, the loan has a
fairly short term such as 5 to 7 years* - and then ends with a single
large payment (the &quot;balloon&quot;) for all the remaining principal.
Most people arrange for refinancing as that time approaches. The balloon
mortgage can be a good choice if you know you'll only be in your home for
a short time.</FONT>
</li>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1><EM>*For example, with a $100,000 mortgage loan amount with
a 10% down payment, a fixed interest rate of 7.750% and an APR of 7.750%,
your monthly payments would be $664.77 for the first 7 years, then on the
seventh anniversary of your loan closing the balance of $89,524 would be
due.</EM></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-1><EM><IMG SRC="images/eqlhous.jpg">Equal Housing Lender</EM></FONT></CENTER>
<P><CENTER><img src="images/banr_bar.jpg" ></CENTER><P>
<CENTER><p> <font SIZE=+1>For more information or to talk to
a sales representative about what Signet has to offer, please email us
at: <a HREF="mailto:info@signetbank.com">info@signetbank.com</a> or <a HREF="mailto:sales@signetbank.com">sales@signetbank.com</a></font></p>

<p>
<br><font SIZE=+1>Or, if you prefer, call us at <b>1-800-2-SIGNET</b> 24-hours<A HREF="mailto:comments@signetbank.com"></A>
a day, 7 days a week.</font></p></CENTER>

